bib_record.title: Measurement of neutron-induced proton-production energy spectra with NE213 scintillator

free_txt: Experiment was performed at the
4FP15L beam line at the Weapons Neutron Research
facility of the Los Alamos Neutron Science Center.
Protons emitted from the target
were measured with three DE-E detectors. Each DE-E
detector was constructed with a 15 15 cm2 and 1.0 cm
thick NE102A scintillator and a NE213 scintillator
with diameter of 12.7 cm and 12.7 cm thickness.The
dE-E detectors were placed at 15, 30, and 60deg
with respect to the neutron beam direction.
A fission ionization chamber with 238U target
was used to determine incident neutron flux.

determination

Experiment was performed at the
4FP15L beam line at the Weapons Neutron Research
facility of the Los Alamos Neutron Science Center.
Incident neutrons were produced by a pulsed
800 MeV proton beam from a linear accelerator on a
thick water-cooled tungsten spallation target (Target-
4). Continuous energetic neutrons from Target-4 were
delivered at 15deg with respect to the proton beam.
An absorber consisting of 10.2 cm thick polyethylene
and 3.8 cm thick copper was inserted in the beam just
downstream of the shutter to reduce the number of low
energy neutrons
Time of flight method was used to measure
incident neutron energy
Emitted protons were identified using E-dE method
